<subsection xml:id="subsection-1-1-3">
    <title>Solving "Hidden" Quadratic Equations</title>
    <p>
        Consider the following super-transcendental equation:
        <md>
            e^{-x} + 3e^{-2x} = 5.
        </md>
        It's ugly, and no one likes it.  
        But it is solvable ``by hand.''  
        This equation is actually a ``hidden'' quadratic.  
        To see this, make the substitution:
        <m>z=e^{-x}</m>.
        The equation then becomes <m>z + 3z^2 = 5</m> or equivalently <m>3z^2 + z - 5 = 0</m>.  
        We can solve this using the quadratic formula:
        <md>
            z = \frac{-1 \pm \sqrt{(1)^2 - 4(3)(-5)}}{2(3)} = -1.4684, 1.1350.
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Those values are not the solutions, however.  
        Recall that <m>z=e^{-x}</m>.
        So, what we have found is that <m>e^{-x}=-1.4684</m> or <m>e^{-x}=1.1350</m>.
        Since <m>e^{-x}&gt;0</m>, we get
        <m>e^{-x} = 1.1350</m> or <m>x = -0.1267</m>.
    </p>
    <example>
        <title>Solving a Hidden Quadratic</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the following equation for <m>x</m> with <m>0\leq x \leq \pi</m>:
                <md>
                    2\sin^2(x+1) - 3\sin(x+1) = 3.
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <m>x=2.8988</m>.
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We make the substitution <m>z = \sin(x+1)</m> and put the equation in the proper form.  
                We get <m>2z^2 - 3z - 3 = 0</m>.  
                Using the quadratic formula, we get 
                <m>z = -0.686, 2.186.</m>  
                Since <m>-1\leq \sin(x+1) \leq 1</m>, we solve <m>{\sin(x+1) = -0.686}</m>.  
                Thus, <m>x+1 = \sin^{-1}(-0.868) = 3.898</m>.  
                So, <m>{x = 2.898}</m>.   
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
        Note that in the previous example, using a calculator to get <m>\sin^{-1}(-0.686)</m> will likely yield <m>-0.75617</m>.  
        To get the proper <m>x</m>, value we use the fact that <m>\sin(-0.75617) = \sin(\pi + 0.75617) = \sin(3.898)</m>.
    </p>
</subsection>